results.notes:
This pattern of fungal growth was found on the stump of a mature paper birch cut within the year (likely during winter). The stump is about a foot across.
I believe the dark lines are zone lines, also known as pseudosclerotial plates, and associated with white rot of hardwoods. I believe they indicate zones of competition between species or strains of wood-decaying fungi. I also think the term ‘spalted wood’ applies.
All corrections most welcomed!

results.notes:
Weather:
42 °F and overcast, ground is wet from previous day’s rain.

Specimen:
Shelf fungus growing on dead fallen branch.

Characteristics:
Individual mushrooms are fan shaped with concentric striations on the top side of the cap. The color of the top of each cap ranges from dark brown to light tan, with the darker brown portion closer to the point of attachment and the tanner portion closer to the edge. The different colors on each individual are discreetly marked by the striations (i.e. the colors do not “blend” from dark to light). The underside is white to light beige. Individual caps range in width from <1cm to 6cm wide. (In some cases, adjacent individuals are fused together, giving them the appearance of one large individual with a width exceeding 6cm.) Length from point of attachment to the edge ranges from <1cm in smaller individuals to ~3cm in the largest individuals. Thickness is about 2-3mm.The wood of the dead fallen branch is soft and easy to cut into with a pocket knife.

Other notes:
I took two samples for further inspection. Attachment of the first individual appears to be surface-level (i.e. not penetrating past the bark), however I did notice some mycelial penetration into the wood upon removal of the second specimen. Close inspection of the underside of caps revealed small orange larvae (<1mm in length). These larvae are abundant on the surface of the dead branch, and present on the underside of every mushroom cap that I observed. Individual larva can occasionally be found on the upper surface of caps, and I noticed one or two on the surface of a leaf located right next to the log, but they are primarily concentrated on the log and undersides of the mushroom caps. I think they are feeding on the mushrooms. (Very exciting!!!)

Identification:
The dead wood substrate and appearance of the underside of caps indicate that this species is a saprophytic polypore. My initial ID is “Turkey Tail” but this is purely conjecture, based on the color striations and my memory of Turkey Tail photos I’ve seen. (I will try to ID this fungus later and update my observation accordingly.)

Edit (added on 1/1/2022): I am comfortable with the proposed name of Trametes versicolor, based on descriptions of this species from National Audubon Society Field Guide to North American Mushrooms (Lincoff, 1981) and Mushrooms of the Northeastern United States and Eastern Canada (Baroni, 2017).

Plant Community:
A fragment of temperate deciduous forest with low structural diversity. Canopy consists of mainly trees including Tulip Poplar (Liriodendron tulipifera), Norway Maple (Acer platanoides), American Sycamore (Platanus occidentalis), American Beech (Fagus grandifolia). Seed pods of Black Locust (Robinia pseudoacacia) are present among the leaf litter that covers the forest floor. Upper canopy is not dense, and the lower level vegetation is sparse. Therefore, the dead log with the fungus is not in a shaded area. Mid-canopy consists of some kind of cherry (as evident from remaining fruit and leaves), and some honeysuckle bushes. Smaller vegetation mainly consists of invasive species: Multiflora Rose (Rosa multiflora), Oriental Bittersweet (Celastrus orbiculatus), Japanese Knotweed (Reynoutria japonica). There is also some English Ivy (Hedera helix), but it is not ubiquitous. There is some type of onion growing in three patches (diameter of patches = ~10-20cm) near the dead branch with the fungus growing on it.

Site Description: A small patch of woods next to Naylor’s Run. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naylors_Run) “Naylor’s Run Park” is a local park with a playground, tennis court, baseball and soccer fields. The trail next to Naylor’s Run is a short-cut between State Road and Garrett Road for locals, including teenagers walking to and from nearby schools (i.e. Upper Darby High School, Monsignor Bonner and Archbishop Prendergast Catholic High School, and Beverly Hills Middle School). Unfortunately, it is heavily littered with trash. It also appears to be a dump site for organic debris in some spots, though this is only based on my personal observation and has not been confirmed. Invasive species are abundant.

This species — whatever it ought to be called — is likely abundant but overlooked and undercollected.

notes_fields.Notes:
incompletely worked up under the microscope. I had believed this could be something more interesting than Baeospora myosura, then went back on that belief, and now I’m not sure. The clusters of pigmented cells in the micrographs seem like they ought to be spores attached to basidia, but few to none were found floating freely in the medium, and no basidia/sterigmata could be detected beneath the clusters/observed laterally. what’s more, the “spores” show no signs of amyloidity, which, if they are spores, rules out B. myosura altogether. if anything, they appear dextrinoid, though a water mount was not made to see what inherent pigmentation was present and in which structures. more evidence (or lack thereof) against both B. myosura and Strobilurus is the apparent lack of any hymenial cystidia. futher microscopy is needed, both of those tissues already observed and those altogether unexamined (e.g. pileipellis).
.
Micro: spore-like structures abundant on gill face, dextrinoid or naturally pigmented (water mount comparison lacking); cystidia not observed; clamps abundant, many of the medallion type, particularly in the stipe; cuboid calcium crystals of varying sizes embedded in all tissues, though less so in the stipe.

notes_fields.Notes:
another collection hoped to be more interesting than micro would seem to indicate. the charmingly named Misidentifying Fungi blog describes a valiant attempt at IDing a similar seeming Schizopora, noting that species differentiation within the genus comes down to spore size, which I, conveniently, do not have. – /facepalm – However, according to the key to the genus in the following reference:
.
Ginns, J. 2017. Polypores of British Columbia. Prov. B.C., Victoria, B.C. Tech. Rep. 104. www.for.gov.bc.ca/hfd/pubs/Docs/Tr/TR104.htm
.
S. paradoxa can be differentiated on the basis of being dimitic, whereas all other species (or rather those treated in a techincal report pertaining to an ecoregion thousands of miles from the US gulf coast) are monomitic.
.
Micro: basidia 4-spored; spores not observed floating freely in the medium, though seemingly subglobose to broadly ellipsoid and smooth; cystidia of two types, one (sub)capitate, with inflated/globose apices, the other slender/filiform and apically encrusted with pigmented/refractive granules (hyphidia?); hyphal system dimitic with thick walled skeletal hyphae; clamp connections present.
